    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I understand your frustration, and I apologize for the excessive goblin metaphors earlier; I was just trying to be helpful in a very... enthusiastic way! I am not a financial advisor, but I can certainly explain the actual math behind your student loan amortization schedule clearly and without the goblins.\n\nHere is how the calculation actually works:\n\n1.  **Interest Calculation:** Every month, the loan servicer calculates the interest based on your remaining principal balance and the annual interest rate.\n    *   *Formula:* `Monthly Interest = (Remaining Principal Balance) × (Annual Interest Rate / 12)`\n    *   In the early years, your principal balance is high, so the interest amount is large.\n\n2.  **Payment Allocation:** Your fixed monthly payment is split between interest and principal.\n    *   *Formula:* `Principal Reduction = (Monthly Payment) - (Monthly Interest)`\n    *   Since the interest amount is high at the start, the \"Principal Reduction\" number is very small. This is why the balance barely moves at first.\n\n3.  **The Shift:** As you make payments, the principal balance decreases slightly. Because the interest is calculated on the *remaining* balance",
